  "prompt": "What's the weightage given to 10th, 12th and graduation marks in IIM's selection process?",
  "response": "The selection process for the Indian Institutes of Management (IIMs) in India can vary from year to year and from one IIM to another. However, generally speaking, the weightage given to 10th, 12th, and graduation marks in IIMs' selection process is distributed among various components, including:\n\n1. **Common Admission Test (CAT) Score**: This is one of the most important aspects of the selection process. The CAT score typically holds the highest weightage.\n\n2. **Academic Profile**: This includes marks from 10th grade, 12th grade, and graduation. The specific weightage assigned to each of these categories can vary:\n   - **10th Grade**: Often, a weightage of around 10% to 30% can be allocated to 10th grade marks, but this can vary.\n   - **12th Grade**: Similarly, 12th grade marks generally carry a weightage between 10% to 30%.\n   - **Graduation Marks**: Typically, graduation marks might have a weightage similar to that of 10th and 12th marks, around 10% to 30%.\n\n3. **Work Experience**: Many IIMs also consider work experience, which can carry weightage of around 10% to 20%, depending on the IIM.\n\n4. **Diversity Factors**: Some IIMs give additional points for gender diversity, academic diversity (e.g., non-engineering background), etc.\n\n5. **Performance in Written Ability Test (WAT), Group Discussion (GD), and Personal Interview (PI)**: These components collectively can have significant weightage, often around 30% to 50%.\n\nEach IIM has its own specific criteria and weight distribution, which they generally disclose in their admission policy documents. Therefore, candidates are advised to check the exact details on the official websites of the respective IIMs they are applying to for up-to-date information.\n\nThese percentages are indicative and can change annually based on the institute's priorities.",
